1921,IssuesEvent,2015-09-03 08:13:45+00:00,3489194,davidhalter/jedi,748594,davidhalter,,,reopened,Namespace packages are not supported,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/davidhalter/jedi/labels/feature', 'name': 'feature', 'color': '02e10c'}]",[],19,"Goto is tricked by namespace packages and fails.

I made tests to demonstrate this issue in https://github.com/flupke/jedi/commit/ad95279f1f5d160a22d5e07c1ced2a3011f39777

The problem is that `imp.find_module()` does not support namespace packages.

Should `imports.ImportPath._follow_file_system()` fiddle with `pkg_resources` (see http://stackoverflow.com/questions/5741362/alternatives-to-imp-find-module for a beginning of solution)? Or is `imp.find_module()` something you would like to discard in the future? (maybe by using `importlib.import_module()`, which does work with namespace packages, but has the disadvantage of actually importing the modules)",{},{}
1922,IssuesEvent,2016-07-06 21:25:15+00:00,3489194,davidhalter/jedi,748594,davidhalter,,,closed,AttributeError thrown when native _decimal module is not available,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/davidhalter/jedi/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'e10c02'}]",[],5,"When importing the `decimal` module, Jedi throws an AttributeError if the native `_decimal` module is not available, instead of falling back to `_pydecimal` by following the ImportError except clause. The native module is only available if the external `mpdecimal` library is installed. I came across this when my auto-completer started throwing exceptions everywhere while editing a file that contained `from decimal import Decimal` at the top. :smile:

This is an example of what happens when the native module is not available:
```python
Python 3.5.1 (default, Mar  3 2016, 09:29:07) 
[GCC 5.3.0] on linux
Type ""help"", ""copyright"", ""credits"" or ""license"" for more information.
>>> import jedi
>>> jedi.Script(source='from decimal import ').completions()
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""<stdin>"", line 1, in <module>
  File ""/usr/lib/python3.5/site-packages/jedi/api/__init__.py"", line 188, in completions
    completion_names = get_completions(user_stmt, b)
  File ""/usr/lib/python3.5/site-packages/jedi/api/__init__.py"", line 150, in get_completions
    completion_names = i.completion_names(self._evaluator, only_modules)
  File ""/usr/lib/python3.5/site-packages/jedi/evaluate/imports.py"", line 414, in completion_names
    for names_dict in scope.names_dicts(search_global=False):
  File ""/usr/lib/python3.5/site-packages/jedi/evaluate/representation.py"", line 720, in names_dicts
    yield star_module.names_dict
AttributeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'names_dict'
>>> import _decimal
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""<stdin>"", line 1, in <module>
ImportError: libmpdec.so.2: cannot open shared object file: No such file or directory
>>> import _pydecimal
>>>
```
With `mpdecimal` installed, everything works as expected. However, it's an optional dependency for `python` in Arch Linux, so this may affect a good amount of people.",{},{}
