I was struggeling with the way figure handling is implemented. 

This does not work in Ipyvolume but many people are used to do it like this from e.g. matlab.
```
f1 = ipv.figure()
f2 = ipv.figure()
ipv.figure(f1) # make f1 the current figure which is then used e.g. with ipv.movie
```

To make it work you have to do:
```
f1 = ipv.figure(key='f1')
f2 = ipv.figure(key='f2')
ipv.figure('f1') # make f1 the current figure which is then used e.g. with ipv.movie
```
If you know it is done like this, you will understand the documentation. But it took me ages to figure this out. I had to look at the source code in pylab.py. Maybe I am just biased by my Matlab past.

I could imagine to pass a Figure Object to ipv.figure(), then figure() notices the type and searches for that figure in ipv.current.figures.values.
So both usages would work.

Thanks

Bye

PS: Very nice library",{},{}
