5853,IssuesEvent,2018-04-27 12:57:19+00:00,12420595,CamDavidsonPilon/lifelines,32672909,pzivich,,,closed,Aalen-Johansen Estimator,"[{'id': 53920842, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/CamDavidsonPilon/lifelines/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}]",[],0,"I looked through lifelines and I didn't see if there was implementation of an Aalen-Johansen estimator. Aalen-Johansen estimator accounts for competing risks, and is preferred over considering competing events as censored. 
You can fit this estimator by using a Kaplan-Meier to estimate the overall survival times. The survival function can then be used to generate the discrete time hazard (minus log transform S(t) and S(t-) where t- is the event time right before t, then subtract the quantities). To estimate F(t,j) you multiply S(t-) with the discrete time hazard and an indicator for j. The Aalen-Johansen estimator also cannot deal with tied event times. I wrote a function to randomly jitter the time data.

It is pretty straightforward. I wrote general code using KaplanMeierFitter() to fit the Aalen-Johansen estimator. I compared the results to SAS v9.4 on a single dataset. I would be happy to contribute it to lifelines. 

Open items: SE/CI formulas, weights, estimation methods, plotting. 

Papers detailing Aalen-Johansen or its applied use:
https://www.duo.uio.no/bitstream/handle/10852/10287/stat-res-03-97.pdf?sequence=1
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5557056/
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4325676/",{},{}
5854,IssuesEvent,2018-01-17 23:14:16+00:00,12420595,CamDavidsonPilon/lifelines,3454453,alexminnaar,,,opened,Survival Regression Stephen Harper Example,[],[],0,I am reading the survival regression documentation specifically the Stephen Harper example.  It looks like Stephen Harper is a right-censored example (started in 2006 and was still in office as of 2008).  Looking at the plot of the survival function though it looks like there is a non-zero probability that he could be out of office within 2 years.  How is it possible given that we know from the data that he was in office for the first two years? Or does this prediction not assume that we have that prior knowledge i.e. we are pretending we are making the prediction when we are in 2006?,{},{}
5857,IssuesEvent,2016-10-06 06:08:37+00:00,28577939,CamDavidsonPilon/lifetimes,3952615,yanirs,,,opened,utils.calibration_and_holdout_data() should work with monetary value,[],[],0,"There's currently a subtle bug in `utils.calibration_and_holdout_data()`:

```python
calibration_summary_data = summary_data_from_transaction_data(calibration_transactions, customer_id_col, datetime_col, datetime_format, observation_period_end=calibration_period_end, freq=freq)
```

The fourth positional argument of `summary_data_from_transaction_data` is actually `monetary_value_col`, not `datetime_format`.

The ideal solution would be to add `monetary_value_col` as a parameter to `calibration_and_holdout_data()` and pass most parameters to `summary_data_from_transaction_data` by name to avoid future errors.",{},{}
