6472,IssuesEvent,2016-10-19 04:04:54+00:00,10674033,marcgibbons/django-rest-swagger,16432,tardate,,,opened,"How to force a DictField to be documented as an object, not a string?",[],[],0,"When passing a dict/hash of arbitrary data in an API, we're using `DictField` (same applies for `JSONField`). A good example is an errors collection, where we really don't want to define a serializer with all the possible elements it may contain. So we declare like this:

    class CustomSerializer(serializers.Serializer):
        errors = serializers.DictField(
            required=False, help_text=""Error conditions, if any""
        )

The problem is this shows up in the swagger UI as a string:

    CustomSerializer {
      errors (string): Error conditions, if any
    }

Likewise in swagger doc:

    ""CustomSerializer"": {
      ""required"": [
        ""errors""
      ],
      ""id"": ""CustomSerializer"",
      ""properties"": {
        ""errors"": {
          ""description"": ""Error conditions, if any"",
          ""required"": false,
          ""readOnly"": false,
          ""type"": ""string""
        }
      }
    },

This is causing problems for API clients that are attempting to introspect on the basis of the swagger doc. Is there a way to define these elements better - at least not have them declared as a string? Am I missing something obvious?

Note we are still on 0.3.x branch (0.3.10)",{},{}
6479,IssuesEvent,2015-08-05 20:10:54+00:00,10674033,marcgibbons/django-rest-swagger,943268,dpetzel,,,opened,boolean type doesn't work properly,[],[],0,"I saw some other issues that danced around this a little, but nothing that hit specifically what I'm bumping up against.

I've documented one of my viewsets with this snippet:
```
        - name: active
          description: Filter on active vs inactive
          paramType: query
          type: boolean
```

This renders a dropbox box with these properties:
```
<select class=""parameter"" name=""active"">
  <option selected="""" value=""""></option>
  <option value=""true"">true</option>
  <option value=""false"">false</option>
</select>
```
So my issue is separate (I think) from https://github.com/marcgibbons/django-rest-swagger/issues/225 (regardless of the select vs check) in that the value is not usable.

Per the DRF docs:
> When using boolean fields, you should use the values True and False in the URL query parameters, rather than 0, 1, true or false. (The allowed boolean values are currently hardwired in Django's NullBooleanSelect implementation.)

When I `Try it out!` the filter doesn't work. I believe for this to actually work the values need to be `True` and `False`. There seems to be a bit of fingerpointing <sup>1</sup> on where the actual root of this issue is though.

It is possible on my end (either via config or code change) to fix that?  The only workaround I've thougt of so far is in the docstring yaml change the type to a string so users could put in the literal string values of True and False, but I'd much rather have accurate documentation on what the type is

Is this something you think should get addressed in this project?

<sup>1</sup> https://github.com/tomchristie/django-rest-framework/issues/2122
",{},{}
6491,IssuesEvent,2017-08-08 03:14:29+00:00,4326308,rbarrois/python-semanticversion,611471,duk3luk3,,,opened,Documentation disagrees with implementation about tuple/list for build and pre-release,[],[],0,"The [Readme](https://github.com/rbarrois/python-semanticversion#versions) suggests that

```python
semantic_version.Version('0.1.1').build
```

should be `[]`, but in version 2.6.0 of semantic_version it is instead `()`.

This makes little practical difference in most cases, except when you do something like

```python
if v.build == []:
    ...
```

which will never work.",{},{}
6510,IssuesEvent,2017-03-24 20:18:13+00:00,5746339,alesdotio/django-admin-shortcuts,15653114,jaredrunyon,,,opened,(enhancement) extending django-admin-shortcuts to all app pages in admin,[],[],0,"(previous conversation moved here)

It's not possible at the moment, but it would probably be easy to add by changing the admin/base_site.html template to include something like this at the top:

{% load admin_shortcuts_tags %}

{% block breadcrumbs %}
	<div class=""admin_shortcuts"">
		{% admin_shortcuts %}
	</div>
{% endblock %}

{% block extrastyle %}<style type=""text/css"">{% admin_shortcuts_css %}</style>
{{ block.super }}
{% endblock %}

{% block extrahead %}{{ block.super }}{% admin_shortcuts_js %}{% endblock %}

Adding the above code to base_site.html will not work because of other templates overriding the breadcrumbs tag.

So, there are two options to make this work:

1. the above code can be implemented in base.html BUT by removing the breadcrumbs tag and adding the actual admin_shortcuts_css tag and admin_shortcuts_js tag to the already existing block_extrastyle and block_extrahead tags appropriately. This is kind of hacky though because alot of other templates i.e. change_form, change_list, and app_index all are using the breadcrumbs tag. This leads to those other templates going to render the breadcrumbs tag but there is none in the parent template.

2. a cleaner approach is to do the above code change NOT in base.html and actually in the templates you wish to override them in i.e. change_form,change_list, and app_index.",{},{}
