7082,IssuesEvent,2016-05-08 12:50:57+00:00,33884891,apache/incubator-airflow,4282712,bolkedebruin,47359,apache,closed,Scheduler functionality to run tasks at start of coverage period,[],[],6,"From the documentation:
```
Note that if you run a DAG on a schedule_interval of one day, the run stamped 2016-01-01 will be trigger soon after 2016-01-01T23:59. In other words, the job instance is started once the period it covers has ended.
```
We would be interested in a feature that tells the scheduler to run at the beginning of the job's covered period, rather than the end.  As soon as the clock ticks over to midnight, the scheduler kicks off the task, based on a DAG parameter.

I *believe* a workaround for this would be to use `{{ tomorrow_ds }}` rather than `{{ ds }}` so that the task that gets started by the scheduler `soon after 2016-01-01T23:59` processes `2016-01-02` data.  However, I think this would cause problems with tasks that are started by anything other than the scheduler.  For example, I believe running `airflow run dag_id task_id 2016-01-02` would then actually act upon data for `2016-01-03`, but I am not certain.

It would be nicer to be able to just specify what part of the schedule interval ""boundary"" you want to be the trigger for the task.",{},{}
