9009,IssuesEvent,2016-09-30 16:57:13+00:00,2640766,astropy/photutils,4992897,larrybradley,847984,astropy,closed,Generic settings to maximize the number of detected sources,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/astropy/photutils/labels/question', 'name': 'question', 'color': 'fbca04'}]",[],7,"I would like to get rid of all non-Python dependencies in [our pipeline](https://github.com/vterron/lemon/), and the first one that I'm tackling is SExtractor. I've followed the section of the [photutils documentation on source detection](http://photutils.readthedocs.io/en/v0.2.2/photutils/detection.html), but I'm encountering a little problem: I cannot manage to get it running properly without knowing anything a priory about the image — such as, for example, the FWHM. Would it be possible to use photutils so that as many possible sources as possible are detected, via some sort of generous defaults? False positives would not be an issue, as in our case they would be automatically discarded at a later stage.

For comparison, the ""blind settings"" that we currently use with SExtractor identify 971 sources [on this image](http://www.iaa.es/~vterron/123m-CAHA_2012.01_raw_120108_ferM_0093.fits)",{},{}
