9109,IssuesEvent,2016-03-30 19:18:23+00:00,2014929,scikit-image/scikit-image,2184487,JDWarner,897180,scikit-image,closed,NetworkX dropped support for Python 2.6 in version 1.10,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/scikit-image/scikit-image/labels/maintenance', 'name': 'maintenance', 'color': '3d8bbf'}]",[],6,"See [networkx/1185](https://github.com/networkx/networkx/issues/1185). Apparently Python 2.6 is now almost two years past end-of-life, and this was used as justification to drop official support. NetworkX still works perfectly fine on 2.6, but that version was removed from the support matrix so pip doesn't recognize this.

As of 8/2, when NetworkX 1.10 was released, every 2.6 build fails when attempting to install NetworkX.

The rest of the SciPy Stack continues to support and test against 2.6, as the burden is minimal if 2.7 is supported. I know of several production systems/workstations which still use 2.6 at my institution, and I fully expect many other systems continue to use variants of Enterprise Linux 6 which shipped with 2.6.x. RHEL 6 continues with full support until Q2 2016, and with security updates until 2020. If we drop 2.6 without good reason, these users will be justifiably displeased.

In my strongest opinion, when continuing support is trivial we should make every effort to do so. We should discuss with NetworkX devs if this support can be reinstated.

cc @ysitu @hagberg ",{},{}
9112,IssuesEvent,2018-04-30 20:41:54+00:00,2014929,scikit-image/scikit-image,9781588,thejohnhoffer,897180,scikit-image,opened,Rescale intensity returns only a float given an array,[],[],0,"## Description

I start with a numpy `array` that has `array.shape == (1, 1)` and `array.dtype == np.float64`. Let's define an example `array = np.array([[0]], dtype=np.float64)`.

If I then pass this float64 array as the first argument of `exposure.rescale_intensity`, the function gives `np.float64(0.0)` as an output instead of the expected `np.array([[0.0]], dtype=np.float64)`.

This is caused by [line 298 of exposure.py](https://github.com/scikit-image/scikit-image/blob/b02e2ce7014f245ff20d692519f2c36ed4bf8269/skimage/exposure/exposure.py#L298)

We should replace this line's `dtype(image * (omax - omin) + omin)` with this line:

```python
np.array(image * (omax - omin) + omin, dtype=dtype)
```

When called as a function, `np.float64` has the unexpected behavior that this is true: 

```python
np.float64(np.array([[0]])) == np.float64(0.0)
```

Therefore, contrary to expected behavior, this is false:

```python
type(np.float64(np.array([[0]]))) == np.ndarray
```

I've raised an [issue at numpy/numpy](https://github.com/numpy/numpy/issues/10995), but it appears this behavior will not be corrected given that the `np.float64(array)` syntax is undocumented. I believe all code that depends on numpy should move away from using `np.float64(*)` as an array constructor. It is always safer to use `np.array(*, dtype=np.float64)`.

## Way to reproduce

```python
import numpy as np
import skimage.exposure

array = np.array([[0]], dtype=np.float64)
output = skimage.exposure.rescale_intensity(array, (0, 1))
assert type(output) == np.ndarray
```
Iff `dtype == np.float64`, instead of `[[0.0]]`, rescale_intensity returns`0.0`

- ubuntu 16.04 LTS
- python 3.6.4
- scikit-image 0.13.1

",{},{}
