9643,IssuesEvent,2017-05-02 17:53:19+00:00,15958352,GetBlimp/django-rest-framework-jwt,8503952,djstein,1227237,GetBlimp,opened,Create admin.py (much like DRF authtoken admin.py),[],[],0,"Many users would benefit greatly from being able to view tokens already made/create new tokens/delete tokens in the Django Admin Panel. Currently DRF has an included admin.py with the `rest_framework.authtoken` app [found here](https://github.com/encode/django-rest-framework/blob/master/rest_framework/authtoken/admin.py).

When the `rest_framework.authtoken` app is installed it still creates a standard DRF token and not one from DRF-jwt. Is there a DRF configuration in settings.py to ensure DRF makes all tokens with JWT? Or can we have a standard admin.py installed with the app with the required fields to show DRF-jwt tokens?",{},{}
9661,IssuesEvent,2016-01-06 02:11:55+00:00,23400136,uchicago-cs/deepdish,902935,gustavla,1261100,uchicago-cs,opened,Blosc compression not widely supported,[],[],0,"The blosc compression (provided by the PyTables backend) is a pretty clear winner:

* http://deepdish.readthedocs.org/en/latest/io.html#sparse-matrices

However, it is not widely supported, so deepdish-saved files won't be loadable through for instance Matlab or h5py. This severely damages the otherwise great portability of HDF5 and can especially be confusing for new users.

I am considering the following solution:

* Make zlib the default compression method. This is much more widely supported (both Matlab and h5py support it, as an example). The compression rate is even slightly better than blosc, but unfortunately it is much slower.
* Add a deepdish config file (maybe `.deepdish.conf` or `.ddrc`) where the default compression can be changed. That way, users that care more about speed than portability can opt-in to blosc without having to specify it every time.
",{},{}
