11009,IssuesEvent,2017-08-19 09:18:43+00:00,30509483,clab/dynet,398875,neubig,2374376,clab,closed,Giant loss for LogSoftmax when Auto-Batching on GPU,"[{'id': 175078385, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/clab/dynet/labels/major%20bug', 'name': 'major bug', 'color': 'fc2929', 'default': False}]",[],4,"Hi,

thank you for the awesome work!

It seems to me that autobatching (on GPU) doesn't work as expected when there is a sum within a logsoftmax.

Here is an MWE (created by simplifying the code where I originally ran into the problem):

```
import dynet as dy
import random

def run():
  b_out = dy.vecInput(46349)
  b_out.set([0] * 46349)
  losses = []
  length = random.randint(5,50)
  for i in range(0, length):
      log_probs = dy.log_softmax(b_out + b_out)
      losses.append(dy.pick(log_probs, random.randint(0,1000)))
  return dy.esum(losses)
           
model = dy.Model()
while True:
  dy.renew_cg()
  losses = []
  for data in range(0,64): 
    losses.append(run())
  total_loss = dy.esum(losses).scalar_value()
  print('loss per sentence: {}'.format(total_loss / 64))
```
When I originally ran into the problem, the sum inside the softmax was an MLP (which is why I need this construct), but it turned out that summing constants was enough to create the problem.

Saving this in session.py and calling
`python session.py --dynet-mem 5000 --dynet-autobatch 1 --dynet-gpu`
I get impossibly huge losses like 1e13 for many (but not all) iterations. Removing either `--dynet-autobatch 1` or `--dynet-gpu`, the loss is about 300, which is expected. When removing `--dynet-mem 5000`, the bad losses turn to NaN.

The problem disappears when changing 
`      log_probs = dy.log_softmax(b_out + b_out)`
to
`      log_probs = dy.log_softmax(b_out)`
b_out is zero, and its dimension is within the usual range in language modeling. Therefore, it is hard for me to imagine how this could be due to numerical problems.

Is there a way of implementing this without running into this difficulty? Or is this a problem inside the autobatching mechanism?

Thank you for any help!",{},{}
11021,IssuesEvent,2017-12-08 18:21:38+00:00,30509483,clab/dynet,398875,neubig,2374376,clab,closed,Passing None to affine_transform has confusing error message,[],"[{'login': 'xunzhang', 'id': 554159, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars0.githubusercontent.com/u/554159?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/xunzhang', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/xunzhang', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/xunzhang/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/xunzhang/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/xunzhang/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/xunzhang/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/xunzhang/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/xunzhang/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/xunzhang/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/xunzhang/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/xunzhang/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",2,"In Python, passing a value of `None` to the function `dynet.affine_transform` results in a misleading error message, making it difficult to track down what the actual problem is. Here's a simple program that illustrates the problem:

**bug.py**
```python
import dynet

params = dynet.ParameterCollection()
W_param = params.add_parameters((3, 3))
b_param = params.add_parameters((3,))

dynet.renew_cg()
W = dynet.parameter(W_param)
b = dynet.parameter(b_param)
x = None
y = dynet.affine_transform([b, W, x])
print(y.value())
```

```
$ python bug.py 
[dynet] random seed: 1672194714
[dynet] allocating memory: 512MB
[dynet] memory allocation done.
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""bug.py"", line 11, in <module>
    y = dynet.affine_transform([b, W, x])
  File ""_dynet.pyx"", line 4018, in _dynet.affine_transform
  File ""_dynet.pyx"", line 4033, in _dynet.affine_transform
  File ""_dynet.pyx"", line 1567, in _dynet.ensure_freshness
ValueError: Attempt to use a stale expression.
```

This came up when I was using the result of `dynet.RNNState.output()` as `x`. The actual problem was that `RNNState` was the initial state, so `output()` returned `None`.",{},{}
