13505,IssuesEvent,2018-06-11 16:21:27+00:00,51040886,Azure/azure-cli,5723682,tjprescott,6844498,Azure,closed,Azure CLI to open many ports,"[{'id': 418939401, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw0MTg5Mzk0MDE=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-cli/labels/Network', 'name': 'Network', 'color': 'd4c5f9', 'default': False}, {'id': 593424290, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw1OTM0MjQyOTA=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-cli/labels/Question', 'name': 'Question', 'color': 'cc317c', 'default': False}]",[],1,"**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**  
Need to open a bunch of ports, **not just one**, to my VM using Azure CLI

**Describe the solution you'd like**  
Able to open a bunch of ports, **not just one**, to my VM using Azure CLI

**Describe alternatives you've considered**  
being able to declare what you want for your VM in a single operation, like #2011

**Additional context**  

I'm following the following to use Azure CLI to open ports  
https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/virtual-machines/linux/nsg-quickstart

I.e., the command, 

    az vm open-port --resource-group myResourceGroup --name myVM --port 80

works fine. However, when I try to open up the next port, 21, I got this:

    Security rule open-port-80 conflicts with rule open-port-21. Rules cannot have the same Priority and Direction.

So 

- how do I open a bunch of ports (not just one) to my VM using Azure CLI?
- how do I add more ports to the already opened set of ports to my VM using Azure CLI?

thx

",{},{}
13507,IssuesEvent,2018-08-16 17:41:53+00:00,51040886,Azure/azure-cli,42447160,zwswim,6844498,Azure,opened,support classic nsg for az network watcher flow-log configure & show ,[],[],0,"**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
Currently, classic resources are not supported in Azure CLI 2.0.  Currently, Azure Network Watcher is trying to launch the feature to ""enable flowlog for classic nsg "" in ignite and having CLI support would be desirable.

**Describe the solution you'd like**
1. if the NSG name is passed in, a new parameter to indicate which the NSG is a Classic Nsg will be desired. The default value could be false. 
2.  if the NSG Resource ID is passed, CLI should be able to understand whether the NSG is a Classic or Nrp NSG since there have different provider:  Microsoft.ClassicNetwork vs Microsoft.Network

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
A clear and concise description of any alternative solutions or features you've considered.

**Additional context**
Add any other context or screenshots about the feature request here.
",{},{}
13509,IssuesEvent,2018-07-06 20:53:41+00:00,51040886,Azure/azure-cli,5723682,tjprescott,6844498,Azure,closed,Allow selecting the protocol when creating an ACI container (az container create),"[{'id': 468695860, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw0Njg2OTU4NjA=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-cli/labels/Container%20Instance', 'name': 'Container Instance', 'color': 'd4c5f9', 'default': False}, {'id': 418947189, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw0MTg5NDcxODk=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-cli/labels/Feature', 'name': 'Feature', 'color': '006b75', 'default': False}]",[],1,"**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
At the moment [it seems](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/cli/azure/container?view=azure-cli-latest) not to be possible to specify the protocol of a port when creating a container with `az container create`. It is possible to specify the ports with `--ports`, but the protocol is always TCP.

**Describe the solution you'd like**
Maybe support it in the same way Docker let's you specify the protocol. E.g. `--ports 3000/udp` or another way that suits the az cli tools better.

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
Working alternatives are:
* start container via""Container instances"" UI of the Azure Portal
* start container with template JSON file

",{},{}
