13690,IssuesEvent,2018-06-22 10:10:13+00:00,17714713,pre-commit/pre-commit-hooks,425560,dvolgyes,6943086,pre-commit,closed,file corruption detection?,[],[],2,"Hi,

I have quite a lot of ideas for detecting corrupt files before committing. 
E.g. image files could be automatically detected with imagemagick convert,
video/audio with ffmpeg, most compressors can detect file errors, etc.
(And there are specific tools, e.g. mp3check, etc.)
But these are a bit platform specific, and require external softwares.

On the other hand, I also often find files which have wrong extensions.
E.g. the program saves jpeg, even when you give .png extension.
Using python-magic and mimetypes, it is not too hard to check
if the file content matches with the extension or not.
(But sometimes it is tricky, many files are detected as text,
but for text, mimetypes do not enumerate this extension, 
so a blacklist/whitelist would be needed.)

The question is: would these kind of corruption detector codes interesting
for merging back, or because they are a bit platform dependent, it
would be easier to maintain a separate repository?

For my experiments, I made a fork, I discarded most existing codes, 
and generated a quick and dirty example here: https://github.com/dvolgyes/pre-commit-hooks 

So the question is: is it interesting idea to get it polished, and merged back,
or should I keep it in my own repository after polishing?",{},{}
