13931,IssuesEvent,2016-11-11 15:24:25+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,2807270,jim22k,7388996,jupyter,opened,list running servers occasionally gives wrong information,[],[],0,"`notebook.notebookapp.list_running_servers()` will occasionally give wrong information, listing servers which are no longer running.

I traced this down to having outdated nbserver-xxxx.json info files in my runtime dir. It seems that there is a bug in the `os.unlink` call which tries to remove these old files.

Normally, having the old files hanging around isn't a problem, but on the rare chance that the pid becomes active again from another process, list_running_servers will show that outdated information as a currently running server. This becomes a problem for things like `nbopen()` which attempt to use existing servers rather than spawn new ones.",{},{}
13936,IssuesEvent,2015-11-24 23:36:07+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,1857993,captainsafia,7388996,jupyter,opened,Adopt pandas-style Jupyter contribution guide,[],[],0,"During the November 24th developer meeting, there was a discussion around the friendliness and accessibility of our documentation, especially with regard to new contributors.

I'd like to propose that we create a new Jupyter Contribution Guide that goes a step beyond the previous [IPython Contribution Guide](https://github.com/ipython/ipython/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md) that we link to in all of the repositories and incorporates some of the great additions @jhamrick made to the contribution guide.

I selected `pandas` as a model for a contribution guide because [their guide](https://github.com/pydata/pandas/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md) was immensely helpful to me when I submitted my first ever PR to an OS project. We can incorporate features of other contribution guidelines into this, of course.

It might be a good idea (and very meta) to have a first time contributor submit a PR for this with the help of one of the more regular developers just so we can make sure the guidelines have the right perspective.

Thoughts?

cc/ @ellisonbg @fperez @willingc ",{},{}
13940,IssuesEvent,2017-02-19 18:48:03+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,27600,ellisonbg,7388996,jupyter,opened,Design of the cell tags UI,[],[],0,"Doing UI/UX review for 5.0 #2142...

Yeah, so nice to see the cell tags UI! This is something we have wanted/needed for a long time and it is so nice to see working and about to be released. Awesome!

Some design feedback on it:

The UI of tags that already exist makes it a bit difficult to see which ""X"" goes with which tag:

![screen shot 2017-02-19 at 11 38 25 am](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/27600/23105222/8821361c-f698-11e6-8b6f-73e41ecdc593.png)

I would put some sort of enclosing div with a shading/border to group each tag name and the close ""X"" together.

Also, the ""X"" on hover gets an underscore as though they are hyperlinks. Let's remove that:

![screen shot 2017-02-19 at 11 40 31 am](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/27600/23105226/ad11b5dc-f698-11e6-9e24-6ec9498807dc.png)

Lastly, it looks like this is just a capital ""X"" character. Can we use a font awesome close icon?

Feedback on the R hand side UI:

![screen shot 2017-02-19 at 11 39 49 am](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/27600/23105232/e30888fa-f698-11e6-8400-bb810f1b282a.png)

1. We try to not use the default browser blue glow for text areas that are focused.
2. The horizontal spacing between the three components isn't consistent. The ""..."" and textarea have a wider spacing that the textarea and button. I would use the larger spacing of the two.
3. The vertical spacing between the UI elements and the enclosing cell toolbar isn't symmetric. For most cell toolbar UI, we use smaller UI controls, to leave more room above/below and make it symmteric. Here is an example from another cell toolbar:

![screen shot 2017-02-19 at 11 40 56 am](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/27600/23105247/403aaa30-f699-11e6-9d83-255684ec698a.png)
",{},{}
