15498,IssuesEvent,2017-01-16 09:53:00+00:00,18302786,IDSIA/sacred,1160920,Qwlouse,11296960,IDSIA,closed,Mongo DB stores time as UTC although the timestamp corresponds to localtime,[],[],0,"The Mongo DB observer takes the current time and stores it into the database to track when an experiment begun and when it was updated.
However the time in local timezone is stored with UTC timezone (without calculating the UTC time).
When reading the database, one has to remember that he must not convert the UTC timestamp to the local time zone, but treat it as if it already was in local timezone.

The result is that if someone, let's say in GMT+2, runs an experiment and somebody else in GMT+1 reads the values, he sees that the last update of the experiment was in the future.",{},{}
