15928,IssuesEvent,2016-10-10 17:50:28+00:00,40328394,angr/angr,22711313,flxflndy,12520807,angr,closed,angr provides wrong results in certain cases,[],"[{'login': 'ltfish', 'id': 5071575, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/5071575?v=3', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ltfish', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/ltfish', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ltfish/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ltfish/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ltfish/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ltfish/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ltfish/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ltfish/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ltfish/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ltfish/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/ltfish/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",3,"I am currently playing around with angr and came along a small issue:
I have created two binaries which read input from a file and call a function based on their content.

The first parsing routine of test1:
```
char *pwdFun2 = ""bbbb"";
void parsing(char* input) {
	if (memcmp(input, pwdFun2, 4) == 0){
		fun2();
	}

}
```
The second parsing routine of test2:
```
char *pwdFun1 = ""aaaa"";
char *pwdFun2 = ""bbbb"";
void parsing(char* input) {
	if (memcmp(input, pwdFun1, 4) == 0)  {
                fun1();
        }
	else if (memcmp(input, pwdFun2, 4) == 0) {
		fun2();


	}
}
```

I have created a angr script which tries to find given function in a given binary.
```
#!/usr/bin/env python2
import angr
import sys
import simuvex
import logging
logging.basicConfig(level=logging.DEBUG) 
#logging.getLogger(""simuvex.procedures.libc.memcmp"").setLevel(logging.DEBUG)
#logging.getLogger(""simuvex.procedures.libc.strncmp"").setLevel(logging.DEBUG)

def getFuncAddress(cfg, funcName ):
	found = [
		addr for addr,func in cfg.kb.functions.iteritems()
		if funcName == func.name
		]
	if len( found ) > 0:
		print ""Found ""+funcName+""'s address at ""+hex(found[0])+""!""
		return found[0]
	else:
		raise Exception(""No address found for function : ""+funcName)
def get_byte(s, i):
	pos = s.size() / 8 - 1 - i
	return s[pos * 8 + 7 : pos * 8]

def main(app, func):
	project = angr.Project(app, load_options={""auto_load_libs"": False})
	cfg = project.analyses.CFG(fail_fast=True)
	addrfun1 = getFuncAddress(cfg, func)
	argv = [project.filename]
	argv1 = '/tmp/input'
	files = {'/tmp/input': simuvex.storage.file.SimFile(""/tmp/input"", ""r"", size=30)}
	s = project.factory.entry_state(args=[app,argv1],fs=files)
	path_group = project.factory.path_group(s)
	path_group = path_group.explore(find=addrfun1)
	found = path_group.found
	f1 =  path_group.found[0]
	print f1.state.posix.dumps(2)
	state = path_group.found[0].state
 	files = state.posix.files
	curr_file_id = max(files.keys())
	return state.posix.dumps(curr_file_id)

if __name__ == ""__main__"":
	
	if len(sys.argv) <2:
		print ""wrong usage""
		sys.exit()

	print main(sys.argv[1], sys.argv[2])
```

The excpeted result is that both scripts run return the same string ""bbbb"" but only the first binary is handled correctly:

```
./solve2.py test1 fun2
Found fun2's address at 0x4006e7!

bbbb
```


```
./solve2.py test2 fun2

Found fun2's address at 0x4006e7!

bbb

```
Am I am doing something wrong, or is there a bug in angr?
I have attached the source and the binaries:
[angr_bug.zip](https://github.com/angr/angr/files/517742/angr_bug.zip)




",{},{}
15939,IssuesEvent,2017-02-10 10:32:28+00:00,13027352,angr/pyvex,617306,f0rki,12520807,angr,closed,"install fails on arch linux because ""cl"" command exists, but is something different",[],[],1,"I'm having trouble getting the latest pyvex to work on arch linux. I'm using a virtualenv. Install works fine with pip. When I try to import pyvex, I get the following error:

```
$ python -c 'import pyvex'
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""<string>"", line 1, in <module>
  File ""~/.virtualenvs/pyvex/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pyvex/__init__.py"", line 31, in <module>
    pvc = _find_c_lib()
  File ""~/.virtualenvs/pyvex/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pyvex/__init__.py"", line 23, in _find_c_lib
    ffi.cdef(_ffi_str)
  File ""~/.virtualenvs/pyvex/lib/python2.7/site-packages/cffi/api.py"", line 105, in cdef
    self._cdef(csource, override=override, packed=packed)
  File ""~/.virtualenvs/pyvex/lib/python2.7/site-packages/cffi/api.py"", line 119, in _cdef
    self._parser.parse(csource, override=override, **options)
  File ""~/.virtualenvs/pyvex/lib/python2.7/site-packages/cffi/cparser.py"", line 299, in parse
    self._internal_parse(csource)
  File ""~/.virtualenvs/pyvex/lib/python2.7/site-packages/cffi/cparser.py"", line 304, in _internal_parse
    ast, macros, csource = self._parse(csource)
  File ""~/.virtualenvs/pyvex/lib/python2.7/site-packages/cffi/cparser.py"", line 262, in _parse
    self.convert_pycparser_error(e, csource)
  File ""~/.virtualenvs/pyvex/lib/python2.7/site-packages/cffi/cparser.py"", line 291, in convert_pycparser_error
    raise api.CDefError(msg)
cffi.api.CDefError: cannot parse ""extern VexControl vex_control;""
:3:19: before: vex_control
```

Apparently the file `_ffi_str` variable contains only the string ""extern VexControl vex_control;"". 

After some digging I came to the conclusion that the issues is in [make_ffi.py#L58](https://github.com/angr/pyvex/blob/master/make_ffi.py#L58). The first tried command is `cl`. This is a binary that does something completely different (apparently part of the cliquer package) on my system.
This fails silently as there is no check for `Popen.returncode`. Maybe using `subprocess.check_output` would be better suited here, since it throws an exception on non-zero exit status?

After switching `cmd1` and `cmd2`, it properly generates the file (with `pip install -e .`). But I guess this might break other systems...",{},{}
