16162,IssuesEvent,2016-03-15 13:07:02+00:00,43645564,ganga-devs/ganga,1102021,rob-c,13271048,ganga-devs,opened,Ganga 6.1.17 hard-lockups,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ganga-devs/ganga/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ganga-devs/ganga/labels/Core', 'name': 'Core', 'color': 'd4c5f9'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ganga-devs/ganga/labels/DIRAC', 'name': 'DIRAC', 'color': 'd4c5f9'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ganga-devs/ganga/labels/LHCb', 'name': 'LHCb', 'color': 'd4c5f9'}]",[],0,"I'm creating this issue to cover any developer related queries here about LHCb users still seeing ganga lockup during normal use (a few minutes after ganga has started).

From what I've seen of people forcing an exit through ```Ctrl+C``` this looks like the formatting part of the RegistrySlice has issues. This ties in with the my experiences that touching the ```getNodeIndexCache``` seems to cause lockups due to something in the Core not behaving as expected.

This could also be unrelated to a hard-lockup elsewhere which locks an object in such a way that getting any attribute from it is no longer possible.
I wonder if we may want to relax the ```__get__``` lock by introducing some logic to differentiate between what is currently being get and set within the GangaObject? Locking the whole object just to change it's name seems a little heavy-handed to me.

Also should the get lock walk all the way up but not reach the parent as there is no way to request the parent from within the get method so it makes no sense to lock it this way?",{},{}
16172,IssuesEvent,2016-01-25 08:40:54+00:00,43645564,ganga-devs/ganga,1102021,rob-c,13271048,ganga-devs,opened,JobTime has no parent issues,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ganga-devs/ganga/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ganga-devs/ganga/labels/Core', 'name': 'Core', 'color': 'd4c5f9'}]",[],0,"Hi all,

I'm seeing a (new?) bug that some jobs can't update their status on HEAD due to the jobTime object not having a parent object correctly assigned.

This object should be being assigned using the ```__set__``` method in Objects.py and automatically picking up a parent. It's not clear if this is due to the setParent methods being subverted or whether there is an incorrect use of setattr over setNodeAttribute somewhere for (just?) this attribute.

This is quite serious and I'd like to get this fixed asap to avoid getting into a situation as with 6.1.14 where these problems plague the release debugging for longer than they should.

Rob",{},{}
16215,IssuesEvent,2017-09-08 10:25:08+00:00,31315021,Kinto/kinto,229453,Natim,13413813,Kinto,opened,Handle a setup.py entry point to let plugins add new kinto subcommands,"[{'id': 180758580, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Kinto/kinto/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}, {'id': 180758581, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Kinto/kinto/labels/help%20wanted', 'name': 'help wanted', 'color': '159818', 'default': True}]",[],0,"In kinto-elasticsearch, kinto-signer and kinto-account we have commands that we would like to run with `kinto COMMAND`.

Because kinto-account is a build-in plugin we did it by coupling the plugin code with the kinto code 🏸 
I would be better to use an entry-point so that installed plugin could register their subcommands.

- https://setuptools.readthedocs.io/en/latest/pkg_resources.html#entry-points
