16288,IssuesEvent,2016-09-29 21:31:30+00:00,11591264,PyWavelets/pywt,6528957,grlee77,13541085,PyWavelets,closed,'reflect' signal extension mode,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/PyWavelets/pywt/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}]",[],2,"I've noticed that PyWavelets lacks an important signal extension mode, which is `'reflect'`:

It would look like this:
`... x3 x2 | x1 x2 x3 ... xn-2 xn-1 xn | xn-1 xn-2 ...`

This extension mode is what is prescribed in the DWT section of the JPEG2000 standard. I assume it is used elsewhere as well.

Please see `numpy.pad`'s `'reflect'` mode as an additional example:
http://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy/reference/generated/numpy.pad.html

I believe a mode would need to be added to three of the four steps (those dealing with the edges) in `pywt/_extensions/c/convolution.template.c`.

I would do this myself but my C is a little rusty and I am time limited at the moment. For someone adept with C I think the existing code for the 'symmetric' mode could serve as a starting point. 

Please let me know if anyone has any questions.",{},{}
