16652,IssuesEvent,2017-08-27 12:25:29+00:00,68483365,graphql-python/graphene-django,26211423,Pursuittech,15002022,graphql-python,closed,Automatically generating resolve functions,[],[],0,"At the bottom of the official tutorial it says

>As you can see, GraphQL is very powerful but there are a lot of repetitions in our example. We can do a lot of improvements by adding layers of abstraction on top of `graphene-django`.

However, in the 1.0 blog post it says

>Ok, it’s hard to do a maintainable Python package based in the in the syntactic sugar magic behind the metaclasses.

I'm new to Python metaclasses and thought it would be a cool challenge to try and automatically add resolve functions for certain fields. I basically want to make `resolve_*` functions be automatically added in simple cases:

```
class Query(graphene.AbstractType):
    lesson = graphene.Field(LessonType, id=graphene.Int())

    # def resolve_lesson(self, args, context, info):
    #     This will get automatically added!
    #     id = args.get('id')

    #     if slug is not None:
    #         return Lesson.objects.get(id=id)

    #     return None
```

I tried to do this by defining my own metaclass inheriting from `AbstractTypeMeta`, and adding extra resolve functions to attrs before `AbstractTypeMeta` does its thing. Unfortunately due to the way the schemas are combined with `graphene.ObjectType`, I get a metaclass conflict. At this point I gave up as it seems like I'm either missing something or it will be a long headache if I continue.

My question is, are there any capabilities or plans to be able to do what I want to do?

By the way, very excited to start using GraphQL! I've only just discovered it today but it looks very promising.",{},{}
16653,IssuesEvent,2016-10-16 00:42:50+00:00,68483365,graphql-python/graphene-django,188257,syrusakbary,15002022,graphql-python,closed,Issue with choices that are translations,[],[],1,"I have a model that looks something like this: 

```python
class Organisation(models.Model):

	CATEGORY_CHOICES = (
		(1, _('Government administrative authorities')),
		(2, _('Authorities under parliament')),
		(3, _('State utilities')),
		(4, _('AP fonds')),
		(5, _('Courts of Sweden and courts administration')),
		(6, _('Swedish foreign authorities')),
	)
	category = models.IntegerField(_('category'), 
		choices=CATEGORY_CHOICES
	)
```

The import part is that category is a choice that has a translation (which is in Swedish btw).
When I query for this field I get this (as an example):
""category"": ""STATLIGA_F_RVALTNINGSMYNDIGHETER""

...which looks pretty weird to me.

The schema looks like this:
```python
class OrganisationNode(DjangoObjectType):

	class Meta:
		model = Organisation
		interfaces = (graphene.Node,)
```
 
If I instead do this:
```python
 class OrganisationNode(DjangoObjectType):
	
	category = graphene.String()

	class Meta:
		model = Organisation
		interfaces = (graphene.Node,)
	
	def resolve_category(self, args, context, info):
		return self.get_category_display()
```
...the result is as expected, e.g.:
""category"": ""Statliga förvaltningsmyndigheter""

So, there is a way around it. I was just wondering if this is by design or...??",{},{}
16655,IssuesEvent,2018-07-25 20:08:39+00:00,68488677,graphql-python/graphene-sqlalchemy,1249802,paunovic,15002022,graphql-python,opened,How to create additional field in my schema that is coalescing two existing database fields?,[],[],0,"I have `Building` SQLAlchemy table which I expose to Graphene like this:

```
class Building(CountableSQLAlchemyObjectTypeRowId):
    class Meta:
        model = dbm.Building
        interfaces = (Node, )

    hers_score = BigInt()

    def resolve_hers_score(self, info):
        building = Building.get_query(info).filter_by(id=self.id).one()
        return building.hers_with_re if building.hers_with_re else building.hers_without_re
```

I want to add additional `hers_score` field that is a product of `coalesce(building.hers_with_re, building.hers_without_re)` fields. The code above works but is terribly inefficient (takes few seconds to resolve the list of buildings). Can this be optimized, and how?",{},{}
