17726,IssuesEvent,2018-02-23 03:56:49+00:00,51625787,vatlab/SoS,9889312,BoPeng,20074389,vatlab,closed,Multi-process file signature checking,"[{'id': 325435538, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/vatlab/SoS/labels/later', 'name': 'later', 'color': 'bfdadc', 'default': False}, {'id': 325435542, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/vatlab/SoS/labels/wontfix', 'name': 'wontfix', 'color': 'ffffff', 'default': True}]",[],1,This is related to #450. I noticed the file signature check is performed with a single thread. Is that the case? Would it be helpful to use multiprocessing for the task?,{},{}
17727,IssuesEvent,2017-11-08 22:15:24+00:00,51625787,vatlab/SoS,9889312,BoPeng,20074389,vatlab,closed,Global default sigil and option to disable string interpolation altogether,"[{'id': 325435541, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/vatlab/SoS/labels/discussion', 'name': 'discussion', 'color': 'cc317c', 'default': False}]",[],5,"String interpolation is convenient, but can interfere with many other Python features. In particular, python already has tones of string format features (`%`, `format`, and `f' '` string in python 3.6) so it can be confusing to introduce yet another string format feature.

The script of scripts nature also means whatever sigil we use, it can interfere with some scripts own sigil system. For example, the default sigil `${}` is used by both bash and perl. The `{ }` sigil used for Python format string can be worse because it is used by R.

This is why we should perhaps disable string interpolation by default, at least allow users to change global sigil. A feature is current implemented, namely, we allow option `sigil` in the file format line of any SoS script, e.g.

```
##fileformat=SOS1.0 sigil='[ ]'
```

Users can also disable string interpolation altogether using 

```
##fileformat=SOS1.0 sigil=None
```",{},{}
